<methodology slug="contextual-inquiry">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Observe users performing their actual work in their real environment to discover hidden workflows, workarounds, and tacit knowledge that interviews alone cannot reveal.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>methodology</tag>
      <tag>ux</tag>
      <tag>research</tag>
      <tag>contextual-inquiry</tag>
      <tag>field-study</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Contextual Inquiry</title>
    <summary>Contextual inquiry is a semi-structured interview method conducted in the user's environment while they perform their actual work. The researcher observes and asks questions as activities unfold. This method reveals real workflows, workarounds, and tacit knowledge that reported behavior in artificial settings cannot capture.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>User interviews happen in artificial settings. People describe what they think they do, not what they actually do. Important context is lost when removed from the real environment. Workarounds and tacit knowledge remain hidden. Reported behavior differs from actual behavior.</p>
      <p>Without contextual inquiry: missing environmental context, inaccurate behavior reports, hidden workarounds not discovered, and tacit knowledge stays tacit.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Discovery phase for B2B / enterprise tools where workflow is opaque to outsiders.</item>
        <item>Investigating reported "low adoption" — observed workarounds usually explain it better than survey data.</item>
        <item>Domains with heavy tacit knowledge (clinicians, traders, factory operators, customer-support agents).</item>
        <item>Pre-redesign of legacy systems with shadow IT (Excel exports, sticky notes, side databases).</item>
        <item>Validating personas drafted from secondary research before committing engineering budget.</item>
        <item>Understanding workflows, discovering workarounds, and exploring complex work environments.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quick directional feedback on a hi-fi prototype — use moderated usability test instead.</item>
        <item>Public, walk-up consumer flows where every session is short and self-contained — analytics + intercept survey is cheaper.</item>
        <item>Highly regulated environments where observation requires months of compliance review you cannot afford.</item>
        <item>A/B comparison of two candidate designs — wrong instrument; method is generative, not evaluative.</item>
        <item>Single-session "ride-along" with no analysis budget — produces anecdotes, not insight.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Framework">
      <p>Contextual inquiry is structured around four foundational principles.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>The four principles of contextual inquiry are: Context (go to the user's workplace), Partnership (user is expert, researcher learns), Interpretation (share interpretations, get corrections), and Focus (clear research questions guide session).</statement>
        <rationale>These principles ensure the researcher captures authentic behavior in realistic conditions while maintaining a collaborative relationship with the participant.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When to use contextual inquiry: understanding workflows, discovering workarounds, early discovery phase, complex work environments. When NOT to use: quick feedback needed (use usability testing), remote users only (use remote variation).</statement>
        <rationale>Contextual inquiry is expensive and time-intensive; it is best deployed early for generative discovery, not late-stage evaluation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Process">
      <p>A structured approach to conducting contextual inquiry involves six sequential steps.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1: Prepare — Define focus by identifying what aspects of work to observe and what questions to answer, select the right participants, and plan logistics including 1-2 hour sessions, organizational permission, recording equipment, and observation guide.</statement>
        <rationale>Preparation ensures the research addresses clear questions and does not intrude on business operations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2: Conduct Introduction — Use an opening script that positions the user as expert and the researcher as apprentice. Example: "I'm here to learn how you do your work. You're the expert. I'll watch and ask questions. Please do your work as normally as possible. If you explain something I don't understand, I'll ask. If I interpret something wrong, please correct me."</statement>
        <rationale>The opening sets the tone for a collaborative rather than evaluative session and primes the user to correct the researcher's misunderstandings.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3: Observe and Interview — Follow a master-apprentice model where the user is the master (expert) and the researcher is the apprentice (learner). Watch silently at first, ask about specific actions ("Why did you do that?"), share interpretations ("So it seems like..."), and get corrections ("Did I understand correctly?").</statement>
        <rationale>The master-apprentice frame minimizes researcher bias, encourages the user to articulate tacit knowledge, and allows real-time validation of interpretations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4: Capture Data — Document actions taken, tools used, artifacts created/used, physical environment, interruptions, workarounds, and frustrations expressed. Capture artifacts (screenshots, photos of paper, redacted spreadsheet exports) — they outlive memory and quote ambiguity.</statement>
        <rationale>Comprehensive capture of context, behavior, and artifacts provides the raw material for later analysis and allows triangulation of stated versus observed behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5: Debrief Immediately — Within an hour of each session, review notes, highlight key insights, note follow-up questions, and capture initial interpretations. Hold the immediate-debrief sacred: 15 minutes within an hour of the session, before context decays.</statement>
        <rationale>Immediate debrief prevents loss of context and allows the researcher to identify gaps while the experience is fresh.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6: Analyze Across Sessions — After all sessions, identify patterns, create affinity diagrams, develop models (flow, sequence, cultural), and generate insights. Build the affinity diagram on physical wall or Miro before letting an LLM cluster — it reveals researcher bias the LLM will hide.</statement>
        <rationale>Pattern analysis across participants reveals systemic insights rather than anecdotes, and human-driven clustering preserves nuance that LLMs miss.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Templates">
      <p>Two templates support contextual inquiry execution: an observation guide and session notes template.</p>
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# Contextual Inquiry Guide: [Study Name]

**Date:** [Date]
**Participant:** [ID]
**Location:** [Where]
**Duration:** [Expected duration]

## Focus Areas
1. [Primary focus area]
2. [Secondary focus area]

## Opening Script
[Your introduction script]

## Key Questions to Explore
- [Question about workflow]
- [Question about tools]
- [Question about challenges]
- [Question about workarounds]

## Observation Checklist
- [ ] Physical environment
- [ ] Tools and artifacts
- [ ] Workflows and sequences
- [ ] Interactions with others
- [ ] Interruptions
- [ ] Workarounds

## Notes Section
| Time | Observation | Questions/Interpretation |
|------|-------------|--------------------------|
| | | |]]></code>
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# Contextual Inquiry Notes

**Participant:** [ID]
**Date:** [Date]
**Location:** [Where]
**Duration:** [Actual duration]

## Environment
[Describe physical space, tools visible, setup]

## Workflow Observations

### Task 1: [Task Name]
**Sequence:**
1. [Step 1]
2. [Step 2]
3. [Step 3]

**Tools used:** [List]
**Artifacts:** [List]
**Quote:** "[What they said]"
**Interpretation:** [Your understanding]
**Participant correction:** [If any]

## Key Insights
1. [Insight 1]
2. [Insight 2]

## Workarounds Observed
- [Workaround 1]: [Why they do it]
- [Workaround 2]: [Why they do it]

## Pain Points
- [Pain point 1]
- [Pain point 2]

## Surprises
- [Something unexpected]

## Follow-up Questions
- [Question for future sessions]]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="Examples">
      <example type="good" title="Healthcare Workflow Example">
        <p>Focus: How nurses document patient information</p>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[10:15 - Nurse enters patient room with laptop on cart
10:16 - Checks paper notes from pocket before entering vitals
10:18 - System times out, re-enters credentials (3rd time this hour)
10:20 - Leaves notes on "sticky" because form doesn't have right field

Interpretation shared: "It seems like you keep paper notes
because the system doesn't capture everything?"

Correction: "Exactly. The allergies field is too small and
I need to remember to tell the doctor about the new reaction."]]></code>
        <p>Insight: System timeouts and form limitations cause workarounds that risk information loss.</p>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Financial Analysis Example">
        <p>Focus: How analysts prepare reports</p>
        <p>Discovery: Analyst copies data from 3 systems to Excel, manually reformats because formats don't match, keeps personal templates not shared with team, emails report as PDF despite having report system.</p>
        <p>Insight: Official tools do not support actual workflow, causing shadow IT usage.</p>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Mistakes and Tips">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Interviewing without observing — asking questions but not watching work.</description>
        <reason>Questions elicit reported behavior; observation reveals actual behavior. Both are needed to identify the gap.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading the user with suggestions like "Wouldn't it be easier if..."</description>
        <reason>Leading questions bias the user's responses and introduce researcher assumptions rather than discovering user reality.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not sharing interpretations — missing chances for correction.</description>
        <reason>The master-apprentice frame depends on real-time feedback; hidden interpretations defeat the method.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Disrupting normal work — causing artificial behavior.</description>
        <reason>The goal is authentic behavior; researcher presence that changes behavior defeats the method.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Single session only — missing variation and edge cases.</description>
        <reason>Generative insights require observing multiple participants and contexts; a single session produces anecdotes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Building rapport: express genuine curiosity, show respect for expertise, thank participants for teaching, be patient. Never judge, suggest improvements, express surprise, or rush participants.</statement>
        <rationale>Rapport determines whether participants share tacit knowledge and correct researcher misunderstandings candidly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Capture rich data across types: actions (what they did), artifacts (what they used/created), environment (physical context), quotes (exact words, marked clearly), breakdowns (when things did not work), and interpretations (your understanding, marked as such).</statement>
        <rationale>Rich data types allow later analysis across multiple lenses and triangulation of user intent.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Remote Contextual Inquiry">
      <p>When in-person observation is not possible, several adaptations are available, each with trade-offs.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Remote adaptations: video call with screen share + webcam showing environment, user self-documentation, diary study where user logs activities over time, or remote screen recording of actual work sessions.</statement>
        <rationale>Remote adaptations preserve some observational signal but lose environmental context, peripheral activities, and physical artifacts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Remote limitations: less environmental context, harder to see physical artifacts, may miss peripheral activities, and technology can feel more intrusive than in-person presence.</statement>
        <rationale>Understanding these trade-offs allows researchers to adjust analysis and mitigate lost signal through other channels (diary notes, artifact photos).</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Analysis Methods">
      <p>Three structured methods support analysis across contextual inquiry sessions.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Affinity Diagram: Write each observation on a sticky note, cluster related observations, name the clusters, identify themes. Build on physical wall or Miro before letting an LLM cluster — it reveals researcher bias the LLM will hide.</statement>
        <rationale>Physical clustering surfaces emergent structure that human researchers then refine; LLM clustering can hide outliers and rare insights.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Sequence Model: Map the steps in workflows, documenting actions taken, decisions made, artifacts used, and handoffs between people.</statement>
        <rationale>Sequence models reveal dependencies, decision points, and handoff failures that single observations might miss.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cultural Model: Understand organizational context including power dynamics, team communication, formal versus informal processes, and values and priorities.</statement>
        <rationale>Cultural context explains why observed workarounds exist and what system changes would actually be adopted.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>Treat the agent as a research-ops assistant, not the field investigator. A human runs the session; subagents handle preparation, transcript ingestion, affinity coding, model synthesis, and cross-session pattern detection. Keep a hard human-in-loop checkpoint between raw transcript and any insight artifact — LLMs hallucinate quotes and over-generalize from single sessions.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Recommended subagents: faion-ux-researcher-agent (drafts focus statement, observation guide, screener, and consent script), faion-usability-agent (secondary pass on transcripts to flag breakdowns, workarounds, and contradictions), password-scrubber-agent (run on every transcript before sending to any external API).</statement>
        <rationale>Task specialization allows humans to focus on field observation while agents handle preparation and synthesis.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Prompt pattern for observation guide preparation: "You are preparing a contextual inquiry observation guide. Focus: [focus statement, ≤2 sentences]. Domain: [industry + role]. Constraints: 90-min session, in-situ, semi-structured, master-apprentice framing. Output: opening script, 6 focus areas, 8 probe questions, observation checklist, debrief template."</statement>
        <rationale>Structured prompts yield consistent, usable scaffolds for field work.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Prompt pattern for transcript coding: "You are coding a contextual inquiry transcript. Mark each observation with: {action | artifact | breakdown | workaround | quote | interpretation}. Never invent quotes. If a quote is paraphrased in the source, label it [paraphrase]. Output JSONL, one observation per line."</statement>
        <rationale>Structured output enables downstream analysis and enforces quote integrity.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Tools and Services">
      <p>CLI tools, OSS platforms, and SaaS services support contextual inquiry workflows at different scales.</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[CLI Tools:
  whisperx — Forced-aligned transcription with speaker diarization for field recordings
             https://github.com/m-bain/whisperX
  ffmpeg — Trim, downmix, redact audio segments before transcription
           https://ffmpeg.org
  obsidian + dataview — Local markdown notes + queryable affinity tags
                        https://obsidian.md
  taguette — Free OSS qualitative coding (BYO server, no SaaS data leak)
             https://www.taguette.org
  pandoc — Convert field notes (md/docx) to a normalized corpus for LLM ingestion
           https://pandoc.org]]></code>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Services & SaaS:
  Dovetail — REST API + tags export, best for enterprise teams, supports highlight reels and AI summaries
  Reduct.video — Transcript-as-video, export JSON for agent processing
  Condens — EU-hosted GDPR-friendly, strong tagging API
  Notably — AI-assisted analysis, treat AI tags as draft not final
  Lookback — Live observation, weak export API
  Taguette — OSS self-host, best for confidential domains, SQLite backend
  MAXQDA / NVivo / ATLAS.ti — Academic standard, no native agent integration]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a 30-minute pilot with an internal stakeholder before the first real participant — it surfaces logistics bugs, not insight.</statement>
        <rationale>Pilots reveal equipment failures, timing issues, and unclear instructions before they compromise real data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Stop at 6–8 participants per role; if signal still saturates, scope was too broad — split the study.</statement>
        <rationale>Beyond 6–8 participants, new observations become increasingly rare; continuing suggests the research question is too broad.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Triangulate stated versus observed behavior in your notes column-by-column; the gap is where the real insight lives.</statement>
        <rationale>Gaps between what users report and what they do reveal assumptions, workarounds, and unmet needs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never feed raw audio/video to a third-party API without an explicit data-handling addendum — field recordings frequently contain PHI/PII the participant forgot to redact.</statement>
        <rationale>Healthcare, finance, and other regulated domains often contain sensitive data; accidental disclosure is a compliance violation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>LLMs invent participant quotes. Always run a quote-presence check (substring search in transcript) before any artifact ships.</statement>
        <rationale>Hallucinated quotes undermine credibility and can misrepresent findings to stakeholders.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Master-apprentice framing breaks if the agent generates leading probe questions ("wouldn't it be easier if…"). Pin the prompt: probes must be open and past-tense.</statement>
        <rationale>Leading questions bias user responses and defeat the goal of discovering authentic behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Affinity clustering by LLM tends to collapse rare-but-critical observations into majority themes. Force a "singletons" output bucket.</statement>
        <rationale>Outliers and rare edge cases often reveal systemic failures; LLM clustering privileges frequency over impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Insight inflation: agents will produce 30 "insights" from 5 sessions. Cap output at 1 insight per 2 hours of observation as a sanity rail.</statement>
        <rationale>Output limits force prioritization and ensure insights are genuine patterns, not noise.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cultural and tacit knowledge degrade in translation; if sessions are non-English, transcribe in source language and translate quotes only at reporting time.</statement>
        <rationale>Nuance and cultural context are lost if transcription happens in a non-native language.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations and When It Fails">
      <p>Contextual inquiry is powerful but has real constraints that affect when and how to deploy it.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Hawthorne effect: presence of researcher + recording changes behavior, especially in the first 20 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>Awareness of observation can cause users to perform idealized behavior rather than authentic behavior; rapport and repeat sessions mitigate but do not eliminate this effect.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Hard to scale beyond ~8 participants; statistical generalization is invalid.</statement>
        <rationale>Contextual inquiry is a qualitative method; findings from small samples reveal patterns, not population parameters.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Remote variants lose approximately 40% of environmental signal (peripheral artifacts, noise, interruptions).</statement>
        <rationale>Remote observation captures what participants deliberately show; in-situ observation captures ambient context and interruptions that shape real workflow.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Confidential workflows (PII, M&amp;A, healthcare PHI) often block recording or transcript export to LLMs.</statement>
        <rationale>Compliance and privacy constraints can make it impossible to bring AI tools into analysis; plan for manual transcript review in regulated domains.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cultural mismatch: master-apprentice framing reads as patronizing in some hierarchical org cultures.</statement>
        <rationale>Research methods must be adapted for cultural norms; a frame that signals humility in one culture may signal insincerity in another.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
